description.plain:
Momodou Lamin Jallow (b. 27th May 1996), better known professionally as J Hus (short for Jallow Hustler) is a rapper, singer, songwriter and fashion designer hailing from Stratford, East London.

A signee of the dance music label, Black Butter Records, Hus is known for blurring the lines between the genres he grew up listening to—from R&B, Reggae, Afrobeats, UK Grime, Trap and Hip-Hop. He is often credited as one of the most diverse artists the UK has ever seen.

Stamping his entrance into the UK Rap scene through his freestyles on platforms such as BL@CKBOX, SB.TV and BBC Radio 1’s Fire In The Booth – often to the instrumentals of his inspiration, New York Legend 50 Cent – he showcased his ability to switch from his charismatically humorous melodies to a more a more fiery aggressive tempo, showcasing his distinctiveness and diversity early.

His breakthrough in the game can be attributed to his 2015 singles, “Dem Boy Paigon,” and “Lean and Bop,” both of which received viral success and featured on various radio playlists. He released his critically acclaimed debut mixtape, The 15th Day, in June 2015. In September 2015, Hus was seriously hospitalised following a stabbing incident whilst also being imprisoned for carrying an offensive weapon, leading to a short hiatus from music. Following a 7-month break, he came back with his debut EP Playing Sports in August 2016.

Hus got his first taste of chart success through his collaboration with Dave on 2017’s “Samantha,” as well as his Stormzy and Ghetts collaboration, “Bad Boys.”

His debut album, Common Sense, featuring the hit-singles “Friendly,” “Did You See,” “Common Sense,” “Bouff Daddy”, and “Spirit” released on May 12, 2017. The album did well debuting at Number 2 on the UK Album Charts, and spent 122 weeks in the Top 75. Hus won Best Album at the GRM Rated Awards and at the NME Awards, as well as receiving Album of the Year nominations at the MOBO Awards, BRIT Awards and Mercury Prize Awards. Since then, the album has become certified platinum and left a legacy—with some dubbing it as one of the best UK Rap albums of all time.

Following up the success of his ground-breaking debut, Hus released his sophomore EP Big Spang in May 2018 which saw all three tracks enter the UK Singles Charts.

In December 2018, J Hus was arrested in Stratford, and later sentenced to 8-months for carrying an offensive weapon, marking this as his fourth prison stint in 7-years. During his stint, close collaborator Dave released his debut studio album, PSYCHODRAMA, which featured J Hus on the sixth track, “Disaster,” marking their second time working together. The song was a critical success and saw J Hus achieve a Top 10 UK Single from inside his prison cell. He was later released on April 5, 2019, and surprised fans by being brought out at the London O2 by Drake.

After releasing his stoic Daily Duppy a week after his return, he followed up by dropping two acclaimed singles, “Must Be,” and “No Denying,” in late-2019 to close out the year, the former debuting at Number 5 on the UK Singles Charts.

J Hus' anticipated sophomore album Big Conspiracy leaked online in early January 2020 and was officially announced later within that week, dropping on the 24th. The album received critical acclaim and debuted at number one on the UK Album Charts despite the leaks, no visuals and no promotion. He also secured the GRM Rated Award’s Album of the Year, as well as nominations at the 2020 MOBO Awards for Best Album, Best Male Act and Best Hip-Hop Act. In May 2021, Hus took home a BRIT Award for Best Male Solo Artist.

songs.title: Did You See

description.plain: After some well-received features with Dave, Nines and Stormzy, J Hus is starting to share tracks from his debut album (coming soon on Black Butter). “Did You See” is the first cut to be heard from the album, and hints at an even stronger Afrobeat influence. With the aid of JAE5’s laid-back, melodic production, J Hus explores a slightly different pace than previous tunes like “Lean & Bop” and “Friendly”, but with even more quotable bars. “Did You See” turned out to be the most popular song from the album regarding the number of streams.

songs.full_title: Friendly by J Hus
songs.title: Friendly

description.plain:
In January 2016, Black Butter Records released the latest single from J Hus, “Friendly”, after building up a swell of support on SoundCloud when the young rapper originally uploaded it. Now it’s been given the full treatment and it’s yet another reminder that there’s a lot more to Hus than “Lean & Bop”.

Once again, it’s a fun, humour-filled rap tune that sees Hus talk about seasoning girls like chicken, making “sexy money” and turning his nose up at ice in his Fanta (it is January, to be fair).

The track also serves as the seventeenth cut from J Hus' debut studio album Common Sense.

description.plain:
“Fisherman” is the tenth cut on J Hus' debut studio album Common Sense and a huge standout on the acclaimed project. The track boasts a collaboration with Hus, common collaborator and good friend MoStack and Birmingham rapper MIST.

Fisherman not only alludes to the drawstring bucket hat on the cover art  of the album – mostly worn by fishermen – but also the new mantra Hus adopted as he went into album mode. He refers to females as the “fishes” and himself as the “fisherman” due to the ease in which he is able to draw them in.

Hus, Stacko and MIST all explore topics of females, beef and money whilst charismatically gliding across a big production collaboration between two of the UK’s best, JAE5 & Steel Banglez.

songs.full_title: Daily Duppy by J Hus (Ft. GRM Daily)
songs.title: Daily Duppy

description.plain:
Released on April 14 2019, this is J Hus’ first single since being let out of prison.

He was sentenced to 8 months in December 2018 for possession of a knife. The freestyle was recorded at GRM Daily before he went to prison but was delayed until his release. Lyrically, Hus references several different songs, from R. Kelly’s ‘Ignition’ to Kodak Black’s ‘Roll In Peace’, and ends with a hint that new music is on the way.

J Hus also recently made his return to the stage when Drake brought out the fellow rapper at one of his London shows. The O2 cameo marked Hus’ first stage appearance since his sentence.

Musically, this marks the beginning of a new phase in Hus’s music, the fruition of which we have not yet fully seen. The tone of his sound is now much more reflective of his past actions and clearly shows the maturity he has gained both as an artist and as a person.

songs.title: Spirit

description.plain:
“Spirit” is the twelfth cut from J Hus' debut studio album Common Sense, and was released as a single in July 2017, with accompanying visuals. Backed by a heavy rhythmic Afrobeats-tinged beat, this track carries on a high vibe but sees a reflective stance from J Hus as he looks back on his journey.

This certainly seems like a personal track, and if not for the party feel to the track, it could be a lot darker. But in typical J Hus style, this is not about getting hung up on the mistakes of the past but using those as a basis for change and celebrating his current success; “Bill a zoot and then build an empire”.

songs.title: No Denying

description.plain:
“No Denying” is the tenth cut from J Hus' sophomore studio album Big Conspiracy and the second single to be released following the November release of “Must Be,”.

Over the TSB-produced drill beat, Hus reaffirms his position as one of the top artists in UK rap game, and reminds the world that the months he spent in jail changed nothing. The track comes as a forerunner, and a taste of what to expect from his much anticipated album.

Having teased the song multiple times by posting videos of him rapping its lyrics, J Hus’s release of “No Denying” further raises excitement around the album coming in January 2020.

The album version included a Wolof introduction, saying:

Yo Hus!
Amulor dara loy ragal.
Yallah mungsa kanam. Aduna bi yep yangsa ganaw.
Amulor dara loy ragal, si kaw,si kanam rek.
Nyepanj sa ganaw, sa fans yii, family, everyone!

songs.full_title: Common Sense by J Hus
songs.title: Common Sense

description.plain:
“Common Sense”, the title track and third single from East London singer/rapper J Hus’s debut album, significantly departs from his usual afrobeat sound. The song, which was released a week before the album, features instruments such as organs, piano and slap bass guitar reminiscent of old school hip hop; this is a stark contrast from his 808-driven previous singles. The song closes with a trumpet solo performed by Rudimental’s Mark Crown.

Lyrically, the song primarily explores Hus' newfound lavish lifestyle, detailing his constant flow of income and flashy cars as well as addressing the ladies, haters and trappers in the verses.

songs.full_title: Big Conspiracy by J Hus (Ft. ​Iceè tGM)
songs.title: Big Conspiracy

description.plain:
“Big Conspiracy” is the title track and first cut of J Hus' sophomore studio album Big Conspiracy. It kicks off with a catchy chorus, with verses dropping knowledge, reminiscing on his street life and subtle socio-political gems. The song sets the album off perfectly, presenting the multifaceted Hus that will be present throughout 14-tracks.

The opening track is another incredible production from TobiShyBoy, who’s quickly becoming one of the UK’s finest behind the boards. The beat bears all his hallmarks, TSB’s productions tend to be heavy on actual instruments rather relying on synthetic sound effects. Hus uses this beautifully constructed instrumental to gives his opps a scathing character review.

On January the 19th 2020, the album was leaked online. This opening song was previous known to the world as “Not True” featuring Jorja Smith. On the 24th, when the album was officially released, it came as a shock as the features on Big Conspiracy and Helicopter saw an unknown artist iceé tgm as the feature instead. Hus took to twitter (in a yet deleted tweet) to clarify that Iceé is his real younger sister. She soon became a focal point, even trending in the UK at one point, receiving major compliments about her vocal work and flow.

songs.full_title: Deeper Than Rap by J Hus
songs.title: Deeper Than Rap

description.plain:
The finale of J Hus' second studio album delves deep into his mind sporting an on-going verse, with no breaks for a catchy hook, something that we got used to seeing from him. The song, itself, was perceived as a reflection of Hus' new-found maturity since his release from prison on the 5th of April 2019.

Speaking on the part of his life that we usually don’t get to hear about from the party-banger enthusiast, Hus carefully tells his story on a slow & melodic piano based instrumental from JAE5. Covering subjects from colonialism, introversion, religion, his incarceration, and love – it’s the perfect way to end the project.

songs.title: Helicopter

description.plain:
“Helicopter” is the second cut on J Hus' sophomore album Big Conspiracy, as he continues on the theme of colonialism, perceived ‘woke’-ness of the changing world around him, and the police conspiring against him. Backed by an aggressive, yet still nonchalant, beat produced by TobiShyBoy – Hus continues to introduce iceé tgm to the world as she features on her second track on the album.

The album was leaked on the 19th of January under the name Hustala Baby, with this song originally being labelled as “No Remorse” featuring Koffee.

Following the initial release of the album on the 24th of January 2020, J Hus revealed (in a yet deleted tweet) that Iceé is his real sister. Fans took to her two features as iceé saw herself reigning in praise on her vocal range and flow, even trending on Twitter in the UK.
